\i\fs32 \cf0 Introduction 
\i0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs32 \cf0 If there is a single word that appears most frequently in discussions of the economic problems now afflicting both the United States and Europe, that word is surely \'93debt.\'94 As Table 1 shows, there was a rapid increase in household debt in a number of countries in the years leading up to the 2008 crisis; this debt, it\'92s widely argued, set the stage for the crisis, and the overhang of debt continues to act as a drag on recovery. Debt is also invoked \'96 wrongly, we\'92ll argue \'96 as a reason to dismiss calls for expansionary fiscal policy as a response to unemployment: you can\'92t solve a problem created by debt by running up even more debt, say the critics. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 The current preoccupation with debt harks back to a long tradition in economic analysis. Irving Fisher (1933) famously argued that the Great Depression was caused by a vicious circle in which falling prices increased the real burden of debt, which led in turn to further deflation. The late Hyman Minsky (1986), whose work is back in vogue thanks to recent events, argued for a recurring cycle of instability, in which calm periods for the economy lead to complacency about debt and hence to rising leverage, which in turn paves the way for crisis. More recently, Richard Koo (2008) has long argued that both Japan\'92s \'93lost decade\'94 and the Great Depression were essentially caused by balance-sheet distress, with large parts of the economy unable to spend thanks to excessive debt. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 There is also a strand of thinking in international monetary economics that stresses the importance of debt, especially debt denominated in foreign currency. Krugman (1999), Aghion et. al (2001) and others have suggested that \'93third-generation\'94 currency crises \'96 the devastating combinations of drastic currency depreciation and severe real contraction that struck such economies as Indonesia in 1998 and Argentina in 2002 \'96 are largely the result of private-sector 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs30 \cf0 1 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs32 \cf0 indebtedness in foreign currency. Such indebtedness, it\'92s argued, exposes economies to a vicious circle closely related to Fisherian debt deflation: a falling currency causes the domestic-currency value of debts to soar, leading to economic weakness that in turn causes further depreciation. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 Given both the prominence of debt in popular discussion of our current economic difficulties and the long tradition of invoking debt as a key factor in major economic contractions, one might have expected debt to be at the heart of most mainstream macroeconomic models\'96 especially the analysis of monetary and fiscal policy. Perhaps somewhat surprisingly, however, it is quite common to abstract altogether from this feature of the economy
\fs22 \up16 1
\fs32 \up0 . Even economists trying to analyze the problems of monetary and fiscal policy at the zero lower bound \'96 and yes, that includes the authors (see e.g. Krugman 1998, Eggertsson and Woodford 2003) -- have often adopted representative-agent models in which everyone is alike, and in which the shock that pushes the economy into a situation in which even a zero interest rate isn\'92t low enough takes the form of a shift in everyone\'92s preferences. Now, this assumed preference shift can be viewed as a proxy for a more realistic but harder-to-model shock involving debt and forced deleveraging. But as we\'92ll see, a model that is explicit about the distinction between debtors and creditors is much more useful than a representative-agent model when it comes to making sense of current policy debates. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 Consider, for example, the anti-fiscal policy argument we\'92ve already mentioned, which is that you can\'92t cure a problem created by too much debt by piling on even more debt. Households borrowed too much, say many people; now you want the government to borrow even more? 
